1456","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1452–1533":"1452–1533","1456–Female":"1456–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Afdød","before 1456":"før 1456","1456":"1456","1533":"1533","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","abt  1450":"omkring 1450","8 May 1430":"8. maj 1430","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Stockport, Cheshire County, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Ollerton Hall,,Cheshire,England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1430–1456":"1430–1456","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1452–1533":"1452–1533","1456–Female":"1456–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Overleden","before 1456":"vóór 1456","1456":"1456","1533":"1533","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","abt  1450":"circa 1450","8 May 1430":"8 mei 1430","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Stockport, Cheshire County, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ollerton Hall,,Cheshire,England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1430–1456":"1430–1456","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1452–1533":"1452–1533","1456–Female":"1456–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","before 1456":"before 1456","1456":"1456","1533":"1533","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","abt  1450":"about 1450","8 May 1430":"8 May 1430","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Stockport, Cheshire County, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Ollerton Hall,,Cheshire,England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bigelow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English or Irish: perhaps a variant of English   Bigley   or Irish   Begley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Biglow","meanings":["English or Irish: variant of   Bigelow  ."]},{"name":"Bigley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Begley  .","English: probably a variant of   Bickley   or   Beckley  , with voicing of /k/ to /g/."]}]},{"name":"Baguley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Baguley (Cheshire). The placename is from Old English <i>bagga</i> denoting an unidentified animal, perhaps the badger, + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’. Compare   Bagley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bagley","meanings":["English: habitational name from Baguley in Cheshire or from any of several places called Bagley, in Devon, Gloucestershire, Shropshire, Somerset, and Yorkshire. These get their names either from the Old English personal name <i>Bacga</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ or from an unattested Old English word, <i>bagga</i>, for a ‘bag-shaped’ object or creature + <i>lēah</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William II de Bigelow Baguley was born in 1430, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William Baguley, was 40 and his mother, Lucy Plantagenet de Corona, was 30. He married Clementia De Chedale about 1450, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1456, in Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1430–1456":"1430–1456","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1452–1533":"1452–1533","1456–Female":"1456–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","before 1456":"enne 1456","1456":"1456","1533":"1533","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","abt  1450":"umbes 1450","8 May 1430":"8. mai 1430","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Stockport, Cheshire County, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ollerton Hall,,Cheshire,England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–1456":"1430–1456","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1452–1533":"1452–1533","1456–Female":"1456–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1390–1430":"1390–1430","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","before 1456":"ennen vuotta 1456","1456":"1456","1533":"1533","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","1452":"1452","abt  1450":"noin 1450","8 May 1430":"8. toukokuuta 1430","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1428":"1428","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Stockport, Cheshire County, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ollerton Hall,,Cheshire,England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kun